{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and negative impacts of using prescribed fire as a peatland management tool?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on documented evidence from peatland studies, prescribed fire shows mixed effects on vegetation. Benefits include: increased moss cover (including Sphagnum) with more frequent burning in bogs, reduced tree/shrub cover in fens, and increased plant species richness or diversity in some cases. Negative impacts include: reduced plant species richness or diversity in other studies, with effects varying by peatland type and burning frequency. One study found burning reduced forb cover while increasing sedge/rush cover but had no effect on grass cover in fens. The effectiveness appears to depend on burning frequency, with more frequent burning showing higher moss cover in peatlands. However, burning sometimes had no effect on characteristic mosses or herbs in fens, and results varied significantly between bog and fen ecosystems.",
