{
  "query": "What different management strategies exist to mitigate the negative impacts of livestock on peatlands?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several management strategies exist to mitigate livestock impacts on peatlands. Evidence shows that excluding or removing livestock from degraded peatlands can have mixed effects depending on conditions and peatland type - while seven studies found no effect on key herb groups like cottongrass and sedges, one study reported increased rush cover after cattle exclusion. Five studies found no effect on Sphagnum moss cover, and responses varied between species and sites. Eight studies on tree/shrub cover showed mixed results with some finding no effect on shrub cover while others found increased shrub cover after livestock exclusion. Reducing livestock grazing intensity was found to increase total vegetation and shrub cover, with one study reporting greater biomass in areas with lower grazing intensity. However, no studies were found evaluating the effectiveness of using barriers to keep livestock off ungrazed peatlands or limiting livestock density on farmland near peatlands, indicating these strategies have not been scientifically evaluated for their effectiveness.",
